SpeSpe app

SpeSpe is a shiny app which creates co-response networks that can be used to explore patterns in microbial abundance data. It aids in identifying clusters of microbes showing a similar response and discovering possible links between clusters, environmental, and taxonomic parameters.

Input files

SpeSpe currently has 3 different input types:

  • Custom input - separate .txt files for OTU, environmental and taxonomy data
  • Phyloseq .rds object
  • MGnify study accession

The user can choose the preferred input type in the main panel of the app.

Custom input

The custom input allows users to upload separate text files for the microbial abundance, environmental and taxonomy data.

Abundance data

Microbial abundance data should be available in a tab delimited .txt file, including row names and column names. Notably, abundance data should be normalized into relative abundances in percentages (0 to 100%). Row names should be OTU/Genus identifiers (can be numbers and should match the row names in taxonomic data). Column names should be Sample identifiers and should match the row names in the environmental data file.

We recommend using data on genus level and to limit the number of rows to max 600, less rows/genera increase performance. Maximum file size = 5MB, so think about rounding and possibly shortening row and column names.

An example of a count table:
ID M1 D1 D2 DR1 D3
1 0.0000000 0.0033350 0.0035920 0.0028227 0.0158378
2 0.0013385 0.0041688 0.0007184 0.0021170 0.0000000
3 0.0006692 0.0033350 0.0000000 0.0014114 0.0000000
4 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.0000000 0.0000000
5 0.0006692 0.0025013 0.0007184 0.0000000 0.0000000

Environmental data

Environmental data can be metadata on the samples or any other measurement or description of the samples. This data should be available in a tab delimited .txt file, including row names and column names. The data can be of any type, numerical and characters, however only numerical data will give meaningful correlations.

The row names should be the sample names and should be in the same order as the column names in the relative abundance data. The column names of the environmental data should be the names of the environmental parameters. Correlations between environmental parameters and individual microbial taxa as well as microbial co-response clusters can be explored.

An example of environmental data:
Sample_ID potno Samples Type Groups
M1 5 5_73_16S 16S Control
D1 9 9_43_16S 16S Drought
D2 10 10_44_16S 16S Drought
DR1 12 12_45_16S 16S Drought/Rain
D3 14 14_46_16S 16S Drought

Taxonomy data

This data should be available in a tab delimited .txt file. It contains information about the taxonomy of each OTU/Genus in the relative abundance table. Row names or the OTU/Genus identifiers, same as used in the relative abundance table, and in the same order. Column names are taxonomic units, such as Kingdom, Phylum, Order, etc. but can also include other groupings based on function.

An example of taxonomy data:
ID Kingdom Phylum Order Class
1 Archaea Euryarchaeota Methanobacteria Methanobacteriales
2 Archaea Euryarchaeota Methanobacteria Methanobacteriales
3 Archaea Euryarchaeota Methanobacteria Methanobacteriales
4 Archaea Euryarchaeota Methanomicrobia Methanocellales
5 Archaea Euryarchaeota Methanomicrobia Methanosarcinales

Phyloseq .rds object

Users can provide a phyloseq object as input which must contain an OTU table, sample data, and taxonomy table. Phyloseq objects can be saved as .rds files in R with the saveRDS() command as follows:

saveRDS(phyObject, file = "phyObject.rds")

The .rds file can then be supplied to SpeSpe. Important: the OTU table should contain relative abundances in percentages, in order for the various thresholds and cut-offs in the app to work properly. Users can perform a normalization step for the OTU data directly in SpeSpe if needed. Also, row names in the OTU data should be OTU identifiers that match the row names in the tax table.

MGnify study accession

MGnify is a platform for archiving microbiome data derived from populations that are present in particular environments. Users can supply a MGnify study accession to retrieve all available analyses belonging to the study. Users can specify how many analyses they want to download from any given MGnify study.

Queries to the MGnify API can be quite slow, particularly when retrieving large sums of results for many analyses. For large studies, it is recommended to start with a moderate amount of analyses (n = 20) and take note of the runtime.

Note: a single sample can have multiple analysis accessions. For instance, a sample could have been analyzed multiple times with different versions of the MGnify pipeline. At the time being, SpeSpe will not remove/account for these duplicate analyses. Please view your specific study on MGnify to verify whether there are potential duplicates.

Network construction settings

Once input data is prepared, several parameters are available to adjust the network construction.

  • Correlation threshold - Determines at which level an edge is drawn in the co-response network based on Spearman correlations.
  • Occurrence - Excludes genera which occurred less that the set number, the default is set at 2 so singletons are excluded from the co-response network.
  • Min abundance threshold - Excludes genera that occurred less, in the sample of their maximum occurrence, than the set number. The default is set at 0.1% so extremely rare genera are excluded from the co-response network. If loading times are too long, it is recommended to start this parameter off at a high value such as >1%.

Network aesthetic mapping

  • Color by - Choose between clusters, environmental parameter and taxonomy to color the network nodes.
  • Edge width - Adjust width of the edge.
  • Edge Alpha - Adjust opacity of the edge. Values below 1 will increase time to plot the network, so it is suggested to only adjust this parameter when youre pleased with the network layout and are going for a final render.
  • Arc strength - The bend of the edge. 1 approximates a half circle while 0 will give a straight line. Negative number will change the direction of the curve.
  • Theme - Dark, classic, minimal are available as plot themes.
  • Set seed - Generate seed for network layout and clustering.

Storing results

Network plots can de downloaded as .pdf files from within the SpeSpe interface. The taxonomic barplot and correlation boxplot from the summary tab can be downloaded as .png files. Raw data files such as node data, edge data and a correlation matrix can be downloaded in the Download raw network data tab.

Example output

Example of network colored by (A) kmean clusters, (B) taxonomy and (C) environmental correlation

Luc R.J. van Zon and Basten Snoek, (2023), SpeSpe: A Shiny App for Network Analysis of Microbial Community Dynamics.
